  <title>Docbook Examples</title>
  <section>
    <title>Indexterm</title>
    <para>Indexterms are used to define the terms that will appear in the index
    that is generated. You should always have at least a primary term, and you
    can have more than one. Optional is the secondary term.</para>
    <example>
      <title>Indexterm</title>
      <programlisting>&lt;indexterm&gt; &lt;primary&gt;start characters,
      changing&lt;/primary&gt; &lt;/indexterm&gt; &lt;indexterm&gt;
      &lt;primary&gt;start tags&lt;/primary&gt;
      &lt;secondary&gt;beginning&lt;/secondary&gt;
      &lt;/indexterm&gt;</programlisting>
    </example>
    <para>
    <indexterm>
      <primary>Indexterm</primary>
      <secondary>primary, secondary</secondary>
    </indexterm>They can be grouped for preference between primary and
    secondary terms. More information can be found on usage of indexterms in 
    <ulink
    url="http://www.sagehill.net/docbookxsl/GenerateIndex.html#Indexterms">
    DocBook XSL: The Complete Guide</ulink>.</para>
  </section>
  <section>
    <title>See Also</title>
    <para>Indexterms have an optional element called 
    <emphasis>seealso</emphasis>. This allows you to reference other indexterms
    that may be relevant to the reader.</para>
    <example>
      <title>Seealso</title>
      <programlisting>&lt;indexterm&gt; &lt;primary&gt;start
      tags&lt;/primary&gt; &lt;secondary&gt;beginning&lt;/secondary&gt;
      &lt;seealso&gt;ending&lt;/seealso&gt; &lt;/indexterm&gt;</programlisting>
    </example>
  </section>
